'''Eli Clemans Northrup''' is an American criminal defense attorney and rapper in Pants Velour.
 	
==Early life & education==
Northrup was born in [[Washington D.C.]] and grew up in [[Bethesda, MD]]. From 1999-2003, he attended [[Walt Whitman High School (Bethesda, Maryland)| Walt Whitman High School]] where he played on the football team. He currently holds the record for the most receiving touchdowns.<ref name=Walt>{{cite web|title=Walt Whitman High School Football Records|url=http://fightingvikings.com/records.aspx|website=http://fightingvikings.com/|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> He played piano and guitar during his childhood.<ref name=NYU/> 
 	
===Cornell University===
After high school, Northrup went on to [[Cornell University]]. While at Cornell, he played [[Sprint Football]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eli Northrup - 2003 Sprint Football|url=http://www.cornellbigred.com/roster.aspx?path=&rp_id=30659|website=http://www.cornellbigred.com/|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=Sprint>{{cite web|title=2004 Sprint Football Media Guide|url=http://www.cornellsprintfootball.com/content/mediaguides/mediaguide_2004.pdf|website=http://www.cornellsprintfootball.com/|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Eli Northrup - 2005 Sprint Football|url=http://www.cornellbigred.com/roster.aspx?path=&rp_id=30763|website=http://www.cornellbigred.com/|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> As a varisty athlete at Cornell, Northrup was able to maintain a perfect 4.0 GPA and became a member of Cornell's 400 Club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornell University - The 400 Club|url=http://www.cornellbigred.com/sports/2007/7/11/The400Club.aspx|website=http://www.cornellbigred.com/|publisher=Cornell University|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Alpha Tau Omega]] fraternity. In 2006, he started a rap/hip-hop band<U+2014>Pants Velour<U+2014>with two Cornell undergraduate classmates.<ref name=NYU/> In 2007, Northrup earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in Psychology with a concentration in Law & Society from Cornell.<ref name=gtown>{{cite web|title=CDPAC Clinic and Staff|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/academics/academic-programs/clinical-programs/our-clinics/criminal-defense-prisoner-advocacy/staff-contact-us.cfm|website=law.georgetown.edu|publisher=georgetown.edu|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref>  
	
After graduating from Cornell, Northrup volunteered with the DREAM Project in the [[Dominican Republic]], where he taught preschool, ran a library, and taught basketball and swimming.<ref name=NYU>{{cite web|last1=Reed|first1=Graham|title=Man and Music in Harmony|url=http://blogs.law.nyu.edu/magazine/2011/man-and-music-in-harmony/|website=law.nyu.edu|publisher=NYU Law Magazine|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> He witnessed racial tension between Dominicans and their Haitian neighbors. He said in an interview: <U+201C>Haitian immigrants were essentially treated as undeserving of rights or protections.<U+201D><ref name=NYU/>

===NYU Law School===
In 2008, Northrup began studies in the [[Juris Doctor]] program at [[New York University School of Law]]. At NYU Law, Northrup was a the [[Arthur Garfield Hays]] Civil Liberties Fellow and ''Review of Law & Social Change'' staff development editor.<ref name=NYU/> He taught legal research classes to prison inmates with the Prisoners' Rights and Education Project, and served as a student advocate with the Neighborhood Defender Service of Harlem as a member of the NYU Criminal and Community Defense Clinic.<ref name=gtown/> He also interned at the Legal Aid Society in the Bronx, the Orleans Public Defenders, the [[Public Defender Service for the District of Columbia]], and the [[NAACP Legal Defense Fund]].<ref name=gtown/> While working for the NAACP LDF, Northrup assisted in representing a client, who, at 16, drove two older teens to a store where the pair robbed and killed the owner. The client, who had remained in the car, was convicted of [[capital murder]] and sentenced to [[life in prison without parole]]. Northrup helped draft a brief<U+2014>filed in Mississippi State Court<U+2014>arguing that the client<U+2019>s sentence violated the [[Eighth Amendment]].<ref name=NYU/>

While a student at NYU, Northrup made a rap video entitled, "Charlie Sheen: Always Winning," that became a [[YouTube]] sensation.<ref name=career>{{cite web|last1=Chen|first1=Vivia|title=NYU Law Student Unrapped|url=http://thecareerist.typepad.com/thecareerist/2011/03/nyu-law-student-does-the-sheen.html|website=The Careerist|publisher=lawjobs.com|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> The song was inspired by Sheen<U+2019>s interview on ABC television.<ref name=sheen>{{cite web|title=Charlie Sheen inspires Hays Fellow Eli Northrup's hip-hop alter ego|url=http://www.law.nyu.edu/news/sheen_northrup|publisher=NYU Law School|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> [[Above the Law (blog)]] ran a blurb on the story, and it became a big story in the legal community.<ref name=ABA>{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Debra|title=NYU 3L Contemplates Charlie<U+2019>s Sheen<U+2019>s Winning Life in YouTube Rap Video|url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/nyu_3l_contemplates_charlies_sheens_winning_life_in_youtube_rap_video/|publisher=abajournal.com|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> Am Law Daily<U+2019>s Careerist blog called it <U+201C>fast and saucy<U+2014>especially amazing coming from a serious law student.<U+201D><ref name=career/>

==Legal career==
After law school, Northrup worked as a judicial [[law clerk]] for U.S. District Judge [[Robert Porter Patterson Jr.]] of the [[Southern District of New York]].<ref name=NYU/> He then went on to clerk for [[Julio M. Fuentes]] on the [[Third Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref name=gtown/>

After his clerkship, Northrup became an [[E. Barrett Prettyman]] Fellow in the Criminal Defense and Prisoner Advocacy Clinic at [[Georgetown University Law Center]].<ref name=gtown/> The [[E. Barrett Prettyman]] and Stuart Stiller Fellowship Program combines instruction in the Law Center's graduate school with representation of indigent clients in the local courts of the District of Columbia.<ref name=prettyman>{{cite web|title=CDPAC Graduate Teaching Fellowships|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/academics/academic-programs/clinical-programs/our-clinics/criminal-defense-prisoner-advocacy/graduate-teaching-fellowships.cfm|website=law.georgetown.edu|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> It trains recent law graduates in both the academic and practical aspects of courtroom advocacy.<ref name=prettyman/> The program aims to improve defense advocacy in the criminal justice system by providing able, devoted counsel under mature supervision for indigent defendants.<ref name=prettyman/> The fellowships are awarded to three recent law graduates selected to participate in a two-year program leading to the [[LL.M.]] degree.<ref name=prettyman/> Northrup works with [[Abbe Smith]] and [[Vida Johnson]].<ref name=gtown/>

